I'm developing JIRA gadget and I need to send POST request to some REST resource. I doing it like that
{code:javascript}
        var config = AJS.$("#config-input").val();
        AJS.$.ajax({
            url: "/rest/testing/1.0/config/set",
            type: "POST",
            data: { 
                config: config
            },
            success: function(data, st) {
                dialog.hide();
                gadget.showView(true);
            },
            error: function(data, st) {
                alert('Failed');
            }
        });
{code}

As I understood from documentation in webapp/includes/js/ajs-gadgets/utilI/util.js I do it in correct way. But instead of sending POST request with param 'config'  which has value from textarea it sends POST request with body '[object Object]'. I dug into problem and found in webapp/includes/js/ajs-gadgets/utilI/util.js next piece of code:

{code:javascript}
            if (options.data) {
                if (options.type.toLowerCase() === "get") {
                    if (typeof options.data === "string") {
                        reqOptions.url += ("?" + options.data.replace(/^\?/,""));
                    } else {
                        reqOptions.url += ("?" + gadgets.io.encodeValues(options.data).replace(/^\?/,""));
                    }
                } else {
                    reqOptions[gadgets.io.RequestParameters.POST_DATA] = options.data;
                }
            }
{code}

Next I googled for example of 'gadgets.io.makeRequest' use and found that JSON object passed as 'data' should be passed through gadgets.io.encodeValues() function for POST request too. So I changed my send request code to this:
{code:javascript}
        AJS.$.ajax({
            url: "/rest/testing/1.0/config/set",
            type: "POST",
            data: gadgets.io.encodeValues({ 
                config: config
            }),
            success: function(data, st) {
                dialog.hide();
                gadget.showView(true);
            },
            error: function(data, st) {
                alert('Failed');
            }
        });
{code}

and got my coed worked.

Is that bug or is that expected way for passing POST data?

